abstract: In “The Lost Year” and “Winterkill,” young people fight to expose secrets and lies during the Great Famine.
snippet: In “The Lost Year” and “Winterkill,” young people fight to expose secrets and lies during the Great Famine.
lead_paragraph: When I was growing up in Leningrad in the 1960s, Aunt Polya, who ran my nursery school’s kitchen, taught me an important lesson about my Soviet motherland. Every day, she loomed over us to make sure we ate every crumb of our putrid buttered bread and drank every drop of our tepid milk. We chewed diligently, pretending our lunch was as delicious as she had promised, pretending we didn’t know she was watching.

main: A Hunger for the Truth: Two Middle Grade Novels About Brave Children in 1930s Ukraine

abstract: His talent for creating realistic documents helped children, their parents and others escape deportation to concentration camps, and in many cases to flee Nazi-occupied territory.
snippet: His talent for creating realistic documents helped children, their parents and others escape deportation to concentration camps, and in many cases to flee Nazi-occupied territory.
lead_paragraph: Adolfo Kaminsky’s talent was as banal as could be: He knew how to remove supposedly indelible blue ink from paper. But it was a skill that helped save the lives of thousands of Jews in France during World War II.

main: Adolfo Kaminsky Dies at 97; His Forgeries Saved Thousands of Jews
print_headline: Adolfo Kaminsky, Forger Who Saved Thousands of Jews, Dies at 97

lead_paragraph: Russia’s Wagner mercenary group has been forced to use more of its professional recruits in Bakhmut to replace enlisted prisoners, who are perishing by the thousands as the battle for the city drags on, a Ukrainian official said. The claim suggested that Ukraine sees an opportunity in Bakhmut, despite the heavy casualties it has suffered.

abstract: The Frederik Meijer Gardens & Sculpture Park had a human face long before it received its new welcome center.
snippet: The Frederik Meijer Gardens & Sculpture Park had a human face long before it received its new welcome center.
lead_paragraph: In 1992, when a group of dedicated horticulturists approached the philanthropists Fred and Lena Meijer to support a botanic garden in the couple’s hometown of Grand Rapids, Mich., they received the best reply possible. The Meijers would indeed help, but only if the scope were expanded to include sculpture too.

main: A Fresh Start for a Walk in the Park

abstract: This may be the Pennsylvania candidates’ last big chance for a breakout performance — or a catastrophic belly-flop.
snippet: This may be the Pennsylvania candidates’ last big chance for a breakout performance — or a catastrophic belly-flop.
lead_paragraph: Let’s imagine that someone wanted to design a debate scenario that captured the high-stakes, uncertain, migraine-inducing essence of this freaky election cycle. (Don’t ask me why. Politics makes people do weird stuff sometimes.) The final result could easily wind up looking an awful lot like the Senate showdown in Pennsylvania on Tuesday night between John Fetterman and Mehmet Oz.

main: The Fetterman-Oz Debate Has It All

abstract: Logan Sargeant is F1’s first full-time American driver since 2007. Can his sport make the leap from Monte Carlo to Miami with its soul intact?
snippet: Logan Sargeant is F1’s first full-time American driver since 2007. Can his sport make the leap from Monte Carlo to Miami with its soul intact?
lead_paragraph: Logan Sargeant, the only American driver in Formula 1, is zipping around the narrow streets of Baku, Azerbaijan, at roughly 200 miles an hour. His head bounces inside the cockpit as a wheel shudders over a rumble strip. It’s hard to hear over the banshee shriek of his V6 engine, carrying three times the horsepower of a run-of-the-mill Porsche Carrera.
